            "new_string": "These mismatches are fundamental to the LKL architecture and must be handled systematically. Every new LKL syscall wrapper or seccomp dispatch handler must account for them.\n\nCompile-time enforcement (not yet implemented -- tracked in Group B \"Compile-time ABI safety\"): add _Static_assert checks for struct sizes and critical field offsets in lkl_wrap.h. At minimum: _Static_assert(sizeof(struct kbox_lkl_stat) == 128) and _Static_assert(offsetof(struct kbox_lkl_stat, st_mode) == 16). This prevents silent ABI drift if LKL headers change or if a developer accidentally uses the host struct stat in an LKL codepath. Also add a runtime assertion in kbox_boot_kernel() that verifies LKL's stat output matches the expected layout by stat'ing a known file and checking field values. The cost is one syscall at boot; the benefit is catching ABI mismatches before they corrupt guest data.\n\n### Group G: Web-Based Kernel Observatory\n\nGoal: a browser-based dashboard that exposes LKL's internal kernel state in real time while the guest executes. This is not a CLI-to-GUI wrapper -- it reveals runtime details that are invisible in normal Linux operation because they occur inside kernel code paths that userspace cannot observe without instrumentation. The web UI makes kbox's unique architectural property (the kernel runs in the same address space as the supervisor, with all data structures directly readable) accessible to anyone with a browser, not just GDB experts.\n\n#### Motivation and Positioning\n\nkbox is not \"another Linux emulator\" or \"another sandbox.\" Emulators (QEMU, Bochs) and sandboxes (gVisor, Firecracker) optimize for isolation and performance. kbox optimizes for transparency: it boots a real Linux kernel as a library specifically so that the kernel's internal machinery -- scheduler decisions, page cache behavior, interrupt routing, VFS traversals, memory allocator state -- can be observed, measured, and understood by students, developers, and anyone curious about how Linux actually works.\n\nThe GDB helpers (Phase 5) already expose this data to expert users. The web observatory democratizes it. A student who has never used GDB can watch context switches accumulate in real time, see which syscall paths trigger page faults, observe the EEVDF scheduler picking the next task by deadline, and trace a write() from the seccomp notification through VFS down to the block layer -- all rendered as live charts and event streams in a browser tab.\n\nTraditional approaches to kernel observation are impractical for this use case:\n- ftrace/perf require root or CAP_SYS_ADMIN and produce text logs that must be post-processed.\n- /proc and /sys expose counters but not event-level detail (you see the count of context switches, not when each one happened or why).\n- KGDB requires a serial connection and halts the kernel at breakpoints.\n- printk-based tracing requires kernel recompilation and produces unstructured text.\n\nLKL eliminates all of these barriers. The kernel's data structures live in the supervisor's address space. Reading them is a pointer dereference, not a privileged system call. The supervisor can sample kernel state at arbitrary frequency, correlate it with seccomp dispatch events, and stream it to a browser over WebSocket -- all from an unprivileged process.\n\n#### Architecture\n\nThe web observatory is an optional component activated by `--web[=PORT]` (default port 8080). When enabled, the supervisor spawns an embedded HTTP server that serves the dashboard SPA and streams kernel telemetry over WebSocket. When disabled (the default), kbox has zero web dependencies and no listening sockets.\n\nDesign decisions informed by studying two reference implementations:\n- kula (externals/kula): Go-based server monitor. Demonstrates the embedded HTTP server + WebSocket push + Chart.js frontend pattern. Single binary, zero external dependencies, tiered ring-buffer storage for historical data, vanilla JavaScript with no framework. Key lesson: a single-binary architecture with embedded static assets (via compile-time embedding) is the right deployment model for a tool that must remain dependency-free.\n- tinyclaw (externals/tinyclaw): Node.js/Next.js multi-agent dashboard. Demonstrates SSE for event streaming, REST for state queries, and a rich interactive UI (Kanban, office simulation, org chart). Key lesson: SSE is simpler than WebSocket for unidirectional event feeds, but WebSocket is better when the client needs to send control messages (pause, filter, time range selection). The decoupled frontend/backend model (API server + separate SPA) is clean but adds deployment complexity that kbox should avoid.\n\nkbox adopts kula's single-binary, embedded-asset, WebSocket-push architecture, adapted for kernel telemetry instead of host system metrics:\n\n```\nLKL kernel (in-process)          kbox supervisor\n┌──────────────────────┐    ┌───────────────────────────┐\n│ scheduler counters   │    │ seccomp dispatch loop      │\n│ page cache stats     │◄───┤ telemetry sampler (100ms)  │\n│ interrupt counters   │    │ event logger               │\n│ VFS operation counts │    │                            │\n│ memory allocator     │    │ embedded HTTP server       │\n│ network stack stats  │    │   ├─ GET / (SPA)           │\n└──────────────────────┘    │   ├─ GET /api/snapshot     │\n                            │   └─ WS  /ws               │\n                            └───────────┬───────────────┘\n                                        │ WebSocket push\n                                        ▼\n                              ┌───────────────────┐\n                              │ Browser dashboard  │\n                              │ (Chart.js, vanilla │\n                              │  JS, embedded CSS) │\n                              └───────────────────┘\n```\n\nComponents:\n\n1. Telemetry sampler (src/web_telemetry.c): runs on a timer (default 100ms, configurable via --web-interval). Each tick reads LKL kernel data structures directly from the supervisor's address space:\n   - Scheduler: nr_context_switches (from runqueue), nr_running, current task comm/pid, EEVDF vruntime and deadline of the current task, per-policy task counts (SCHED_OTHER, SCHED_FIFO, SCHED_RR, SCHED_BATCH, SCHED_IDLE).\n   - Interrupts: softirq counts (from kernel_stat per-CPU arrays -- TIMER, NET_RX, NET_TX, BLOCK, SCHED, etc.), hardirq counts (virtio block, virtio net completions).\n   - Memory: buddy allocator free pages per order (from zone->free_area[]), slab cache occupancy (active objects, total slabs per cache), page cache size (from global_node_page_state), anonymous page count, total/free/available memory.\n   - Page faults: pgfault/pgmajfault counters from vm_event_states. These are meaningful in LKL when the guest triggers file-backed mmap faults through shadow FDs.\n   - VFS: counts of open/read/write/close/stat/getdents operations (instrumented in seccomp_dispatch.c, not LKL-internal -- this counts supervisor-level dispatches, which correspond 1:1 to guest syscalls).\n   - Block I/O: sectors read/written, I/O requests completed (from the virtio-blk device stats or block layer accounting).\n   - Network (when --net enabled): packets TX/RX, bytes TX/RX, TCP connection count, from LKL's net_device stats and SNMP counters.\n   The sampler packages these into a compact JSON snapshot and pushes to all connected WebSocket clients.\n\n2. Event logger (src/web_events.c): captures discrete kernel events (not periodic samples) and streams them as they occur:\n   - Syscall dispatch events: syscall name, args summary, disposition (LKL forward / CONTINUE / EPERM / ENOSYS), return value, latency_ns. Generated from the dispatch loop (complements --trace-format=json from Group E but with structured WebSocket delivery instead of stdout).\n   - Context switch events: prev task -> next task, reason (voluntary yield, preemption, sleep). Requires a lightweight hook at schedule() or __schedule() -- either a kprobe-style trampoline or a compile-time instrumentation point in LKL.\n   - Page fault events: faulting address, fault type (minor/major), resolution (page cache hit, disk read, COW). Requires instrumentation at handle_mm_fault or the page fault entry.\n   - Process lifecycle: fork (clone3 dispatch), exec (forward_execve), exit (forward_exit_group). Already observable from the dispatch loop.\n   - Memory allocation events (optional, high volume): __alloc_pages order and gfp_mask, kmem_cache_alloc cache name. Sampled (not every allocation) to avoid overwhelming the WebSocket.\n   Events are timestamped (clock_gettime CLOCK_MONOTONIC) and delivered as individual JSON messages on the WebSocket. The browser accumulates them in a circular buffer (configurable, default 10000 events).\n\n3. Embedded HTTP server (src/web_server.c): minimal HTTP/1.1 server, no external library dependency. Serves the SPA from compiled-in static assets (HTML, JS, CSS converted to C byte arrays at build time via xxd or a custom script, similar to kula's go:embed pattern). Handles WebSocket upgrade (RFC 6455 -- the protocol is simple enough to implement in ~300 lines of C; alternatively, link against a minimal WebSocket library like libwebsockets or wslay if the complexity exceeds what's reasonable for hand-rolled C). CORS headers for local development. No authentication (the dashboard is a local diagnostic tool, not a remote management interface; bind to 127.0.0.1 by default, --web-bind for override).\n\n4. Frontend SPA (web/): vanilla JavaScript + Chart.js (following kula's proven approach -- no React, no build toolchain, no npm). Files:\n   - index.html: single-page layout with chart containers, event feed, system overview panel.\n   - js/state.js: shared state, WebSocket connection, Chart.js global config.\n   - js/charts.js: Chart.js time-series instances for scheduler, memory, I/O, network metrics. Line charts for counters over time, stacked area for memory breakdown, bar charts for interrupt distribution.\n   - js/events.js: scrolling event feed with color-coded syscall/scheduler/memory/fault events. Filter controls per event type. Click-to-expand for full event detail.\n   - js/gauges.js: SVG gauges for real-time snapshot values (CPU load, memory pressure, FD table occupancy, context switch rate).\n   - js/websocket.js: WebSocket connection management, reconnect logic, pause/resume control messages.\n   - js/controls.js: time range selection, sampling rate adjustment, event filter toggles, chart zoom.\n   - style.css: clean layout, dark/light theme toggle, responsive for laptop screens.\n\n#### Telemetry Data Sources (LKL-Specific)\n\nThese are the kernel internals that the web observatory makes visible -- data that is normally inaccessible without kernel instrumentation:\n\n| Metric | LKL Source | Why It Matters |\n|--------|-----------|----------------|\n| Context switches | `runqueue->nr_switches` | Quantifies scheduling overhead. Correlate with syscall rate to understand per-syscall scheduling cost. |\n| EEVDF deadline/vruntime | `task_struct->se.deadline`, `.vruntime` | Shows how the kernel picks which task runs next. Invisible in /proc on production systems. |\n| Runqueue depth | `runqueue->nr_running` | Reveals contention. A runqueue depth > 1 means tasks are waiting -- visible nowhere else without ftrace. |\n| Softirq counts | `irq_stat[cpu].softirq_pending`, `kstat_softirqs_cpu()` | Shows deferred work: TIMER_SOFTIRQ fires on every tick, NET_RX on packet arrival, BLOCK_SOFTIRQ on I/O completion. Students see the interrupt-to-softirq-to-handler chain in real time. |\n| Buddy allocator state | `zone->free_area[order].nr_free` | Shows memory fragmentation per order (0=4KB, 1=8KB, ..., 10=4MB). Watching free counts drop during allocation bursts and recover during reclaim is the textbook buddy allocator visualization made live. |\n| Slab cache occupancy | `kmem_cache->num_active`, `->num_slabs` | Shows kernel object allocation patterns. dentry cache, inode cache, and task_struct cache activity reveals VFS and process management overhead. |\n| Page cache size | `global_node_page_state(NR_FILE_PAGES)` | Shows how much memory is used for file caching. Correlate with read patterns to understand the kernel's caching strategy. |\n| Page faults | `vm_event_states.event[PGFAULT]`, `[PGMAJFAULT]` | Minor faults = page table setup (fast). Major faults = disk read required (slow). The ratio reveals working set fitness. |\n| VFS operation counts | Instrumented in seccomp_dispatch.c | Per-syscall-family counters (open, read, write, stat, getdents, etc.) show the I/O profile of the guest workload. |\n| Block I/O requests | `bdev->bd_stats` or request queue counters | Sectors read/written, I/O queue depth. Correlate with VFS operations to see the amplification from logical I/O to physical I/O. |\n| Network packets | `net_device->stats` (rx_packets, tx_packets, rx_bytes, tx_bytes) | When --net is active, shows packet flow through LKL's TCP/IP stack. |\n| Seccomp dispatch latency | Timed in kbox's dispatch loop | Per-syscall mediation overhead. The dominant performance cost in kbox -- making it visible helps students understand where time goes. |\n\n#### Dashboard Panels\n\nThe SPA is organized into focused panels, each revealing a different kernel subsystem:\n\n1. System Overview (top bar): guest binary name, uptime, total syscalls dispatched, total context switches, current memory usage, FD table occupancy (used/max). Static gauges updated every sample.\n\n2. Syscall Activity (main panel): stacked time-series chart of syscall dispatch rate by family (file I/O, directory, FD ops, identity, memory, signals, scheduler, other). Below it, a latency heatmap showing per-syscall-type median and p99 latency. This panel answers: \"what is the guest doing right now, and how much does each syscall cost?\"\n\n3. Scheduler (panel): context switch rate over time, runqueue depth, current task identity, EEVDF deadline/vruntime progression. For the advanced view: a Gantt-style timeline showing which task is running in each time slice (feasible because LKL is single-CPU, so the timeline is linear). This panel answers: \"how is the kernel dividing CPU time, and why?\"\n\n4. Memory (panel): stacked area chart of memory breakdown (free, page cache, slab, anonymous, buddy allocator per-order). Page fault rate (minor vs major) overlaid. Slab cache table showing top-N caches by occupancy. This panel answers: \"where is memory going, and is the kernel caching effectively?\"\n\n5. Interrupts and Softirqs (panel): bar chart of softirq type distribution (TIMER, NET_RX, NET_TX, BLOCK, SCHED, etc.) updated per sample. Interrupt rate over time. This panel answers: \"what deferred work is the kernel doing, and what triggers it?\"\n\n6. Block I/O (panel): I/O request rate and throughput (sectors/s), read vs write split, I/O queue depth. Correlate with VFS operations to show the filesystem amplification (one read() may trigger zero I/O requests if the page cache is warm, or multiple if readahead kicks in). This panel answers: \"how does logical I/O map to physical I/O?\"\n\n7. Network (panel, visible when --net active): packet rate, throughput, TCP connection count, retransmit rate. This panel answers: \"what is happening in LKL's TCP/IP stack?\"\n\n8. Event Feed (bottom or sidebar): scrolling list of discrete events (syscall dispatches, context switches, page faults, process lifecycle). Color-coded by type. Filterable. Click to expand full detail (all syscall args, return value, stack context). Pausable. This is the \"live trace\" -- the equivalent of strace + ftrace + perf in a single scrollable feed.\n\n#### Implementation Plan\n\nDependencies: Groups A-C must be substantially complete (the core supervisor and dispatch loop must be stable before instrumenting it). The telemetry sampler reads LKL data structures that are also read by GDB helpers (Phase 5) -- the address calculation and struct traversal logic can be shared.\n\nPhase 1 -- Telemetry infrastructure (no web UI yet):\n- [ ] Define telemetry snapshot struct (C struct mirroring the JSON schema). Include all metrics from the table above. Version the struct for forward compatibility.\n- [ ] Implement telemetry sampler: timer-driven function that reads LKL kernel data structures and populates the snapshot struct. Start with scheduler counters and memory stats (these are the most visually compelling and the easiest to read -- single struct dereferences, no list traversal).\n- [ ] Implement syscall dispatch instrumentation: add lightweight counters and latency tracking to the dispatch loop. Must be zero-cost when --web is not enabled (compile-time or runtime flag guard). Use clock_gettime(CLOCK_MONOTONIC) for latency; the cost is ~25ns per call, negligible compared to the ~15-60us per dispatched syscall.\n- [ ] Wire telemetry to --trace-format=json (Group E) as an intermediate output: the JSON trace already captures per-syscall events; extend it with the periodic snapshot data. This validates the data collection before the web frontend exists.\n\nPhase 2 -- Embedded HTTP server and WebSocket:\n- [ ] Implement minimal HTTP/1.1 server (src/web_server.c). Serve static files from compiled-in byte arrays. Handle GET for SPA assets, GET /api/snapshot for current state, WebSocket upgrade on /ws. Bind to 127.0.0.1:PORT. Non-blocking I/O integrated into the supervisor's event loop (epoll alongside the seccomp notification FD).\n- [ ] Implement WebSocket framing (RFC 6455). The protocol is straightforward for text frames: 2-byte header + optional 4-byte mask + payload. Server-to-client frames are unmasked. Client-to-server frames are masked (XOR with 4-byte key). Handle ping/pong for keepalive. Close handshake. The entire framing layer is ~200-300 lines of C.\n- [ ] Evaluate libwebsockets or wslay as alternatives to hand-rolled WebSocket. If the hand-rolled implementation exceeds ~500 lines or introduces subtle bugs (fragmentation, large frames, UTF-8 validation), switch to a minimal library. wslay (https://github.com/tatsuhiro-t/wslay) is ~2000 lines of C with no dependencies -- reasonable to vendor.\n- [ ] Static asset embedding: build step that converts web/* files to C byte arrays (e.g., `xxd -i web/index.html > src/web_assets.c`). Makefile target: `make web-assets`. The embedded assets are compiled into the kbox binary. No runtime file dependency.\n- [ ] Client connection management: track connected WebSocket clients in a list. Broadcast telemetry snapshots and events to all clients. Drop slow clients (non-blocking send, skip if send buffer full). Limit max connections (default 8 -- this is a local diagnostic tool, not a production service).\n\nPhase 3 -- Frontend SPA:\n- [ ] Implement the dashboard SPA (web/ directory). Chart.js for time-series visualization. Vanilla JavaScript, no build toolchain. Follow kula's proven architecture: state.js -> charts.js -> events.js -> websocket.js -> controls.js -> main.js. Dark/light theme. Responsive layout.\n- [ ] Implement event feed panel with filtering and detail expansion. This is the highest-value panel -- it replaces strace + ftrace in a browser.\n- [ ] Implement scheduler panel with EEVDF deadline visualization. This is the most novel visualization -- no existing tool shows EEVDF scheduling decisions in real time.\n- [ ] Implement memory panel with buddy allocator order distribution. Textbook visualization made live.\n- [ ] Implement syscall activity panel with latency heatmap.\n- [ ] Implement interrupt/softirq, block I/O, and network panels.\n\nPhase 4 -- Integration and polish:\n- [ ] Historical data: implement a ring buffer (in-memory, not file-backed -- unlike kula, kbox sessions are short-lived) that stores the last N minutes of snapshots. Serve via GET /api/history?from=T1&to=T2. Enable time-range selection in the frontend.\n- [ ] Pause/resume: WebSocket control message from client to server. When paused, the sampler continues but does not push to that client. The client can request a catch-up burst when resuming.\n- [ ] Chart zoom: Chart.js zoom plugin for drag-select time ranges (following kula's implementation). Synchronize zoom across related charts (scheduler + syscall activity should show the same time window).\n- [ ] Export: download current chart data as CSV or the event feed as JSON. For offline analysis or inclusion in lab reports.\n- [ ] Integration test: boot kbox with --web, run a guest workload, fetch /api/snapshot via curl, verify JSON contains expected fields with plausible values.\n\n#### What the Web UI Is NOT\n\n- Not a remote management interface. It is a local diagnostic tool bound to 127.0.0.1 by default. No authentication, no TLS, no multi-user support. If remote access is needed, use SSH port forwarding.\n- Not a replacement for GDB. GDB provides interactive breakpoints, single-stepping, and arbitrary memory inspection. The web UI provides continuous, non-intrusive observation of aggregate metrics and event streams. They are complementary: the web UI shows \"what is happening\" at a high level; GDB shows \"why\" at the instruction level.\n- Not a performance monitoring tool in the Prometheus/Grafana sense. It does not scrape, store long-term, or alert. It is a live window into a short-lived educational session.\n- Not a CLI wrapper. The web UI surfaces data that the CLI cannot provide: live kernel-internal state (buddy allocator orders, EEVDF deadlines, softirq distribution, slab cache occupancy) that exists only in LKL's in-process data structures. The CLI flags (--trace-format=json, --verbose) produce per-syscall traces; the web UI adds periodic kernel state snapshots, event correlation, and visual presentation.",
