            "new_string": "#### Architecture\n\nThe web observatory is an optional component activated by `--web[=PORT]` (default port 8080). When enabled, the supervisor spawns an embedded HTTP server that serves the dashboard SPA and streams kernel telemetry. When disabled (the default), kbox has zero web dependencies and no listening sockets.\n\nDesign decisions informed by studying three reference implementations:\n- kula (externals/kula): Go-based server monitor. Single binary, embedded assets, WebSocket push, Chart.js frontend, tiered ring-buffer storage. Key lesson: single-binary with compiled-in assets is the right deployment model.\n- tinyclaw (externals/tinyclaw): Node.js multi-agent dashboard. SSE for events, REST for state, rich interactive UI. Key lesson: SSE is simpler than WebSocket for unidirectional event feeds.\n- agentkernel (externals/agentkernel): Rust-based microVM runtime. SSE for real-time events, HTTP polling for state snapshots, Prometheus /metrics endpoint, separate /stats health-check endpoint. No WebSocket at all -- SSE + HTTP covers all needs. Key lessons: (a) SSE eliminates WebSocket framing complexity (no RFC 6455 masking, no upgrade handshake, no ping/pong -- just `text/event-stream` over plain HTTP), (b) browser `EventSource` API handles reconnection automatically, (c) control messages (pause/filter) go over plain HTTP POST (not WebSocket), (d) Prometheus /metrics enables integration with existing monitoring infrastructure, (e) a /stats endpoint for health checks is trivial and useful.\n\nkbox adopts SSE + HTTP polling (agentkernel's pattern) with embedded assets (kula's pattern):\n\n```\nLKL kernel (in-process)          kbox supervisor\n+----------------------+    +---------------------------+\n| scheduler counters   |    | seccomp dispatch loop     |\n| page cache stats     |<---| telemetry sampler (100ms) |\n| interrupt counters   |    | event ring buffer (256)   |\n| VFS operation counts |    |                           |\n| memory allocator     |    | embedded HTTP server      |\n| network stack stats  |    |   +- GET /           SPA  |\n+----------------------+    |   +- GET /api/snapshot     |\n                            |   +- GET /api/events  SSE  |\n                            |   +- GET /metrics  Prom.   |\n                            |   +- POST /api/control     |\n                            +-----------+---------------+\n                                        | SSE push + polling\n                                        v\n                              +--------------------+\n                              | Browser dashboard  |\n                              | (Chart.js, vanilla |\n                              |  JS, embedded CSS) |\n                              +--------------------+\n```\n\nWhy SSE over WebSocket: the telemetry flow is unidirectional (server -> browser). SSE handles this natively -- `Content-Type: text/event-stream`, one event per `data:` line, `event:` field for type discrimination. The browser's `EventSource` API reconnects automatically on disconnect. Control messages (pause, resume, filter changes) go from the browser to the server via plain HTTP POST to /api/control -- no need for a bidirectional channel. This eliminates ~300 lines of WebSocket framing code (RFC 6455 masking, ping/pong, close handshake, fragmentation) and the associated attack surface.\n\nAPI endpoints:\n\n| Endpoint | Method | Purpose |\n|----------|--------|---------|\n| `/` | GET | Serve dashboard SPA (compiled-in HTML/JS/CSS) |\n| `/api/snapshot` | GET | Current telemetry snapshot (JSON). Frontend polls every 3s. |\n| `/api/events` | GET | SSE stream of discrete events (syscall dispatches, context switches, page faults, process lifecycle). Filter via `?type=syscall,sched,fault` query param. |\n| `/api/history` | GET | Historical snapshots from ring buffer. `?from=T1&to=T2&points=N` |\n| `/api/control` | POST | Control commands: `{\"action\":\"pause\"}`, `{\"action\":\"resume\"}`, `{\"action\":\"set_interval\",\"ms\":200}` |\n| `/metrics` | GET | Prometheus text format. Counters for syscall dispatch (by family), context switches, page faults, memory usage, FD table occupancy, dispatch latency histograms. Compatible with `prometheus`/`grafana` scraping. |\n| `/stats` | GET | Health check: `{\"uptime_s\":N,\"syscall_count\":N,\"guest\":\"binary_name\",\"lkl_mem_used_mb\":N}` |\n\nComponents:\n\n1. Telemetry sampler (src/web_telemetry.c): timer-driven (default 100ms, --web-interval). Reads LKL kernel data structures directly from the supervisor's address space:\n   - Scheduler: nr_context_switches, nr_running, current task comm/pid, EEVDF vruntime/deadline, per-policy task counts.\n   - Interrupts: softirq counts (TIMER, NET_RX, NET_TX, BLOCK, SCHED), hardirq counts.\n   - Memory: buddy allocator free pages per order, slab cache occupancy, page cache size, total/free/available.\n   - Page faults: pgfault/pgmajfault counters.\n   - VFS: per-family syscall dispatch counters (instrumented in seccomp_dispatch.c).\n   - Block I/O: sectors read/written, I/O requests completed.\n   - Network (when --net enabled): packets/bytes TX/RX, TCP connection count.\n   Packages into a versioned JSON snapshot struct. Stored in an in-memory ring buffer (last N minutes). Served via GET /api/snapshot (latest) and GET /api/history (range query).\n\n2. Event bus (src/web_events.c): internal ring buffer (256 events, following agentkernel's broadcast channel pattern). Captures discrete kernel events as they occur:\n   - Syscall dispatch: name, args summary, disposition, return value, latency_ns. From the dispatch loop.\n   - Context switches: prev -> next task, reason. Requires lightweight hook at __schedule().\n   - Page faults: address, type (minor/major). Requires instrumentation at handle_mm_fault.\n   - Process lifecycle: fork/exec/exit. Already observable from dispatch loop.\n   Events are timestamped (CLOCK_MONOTONIC) and delivered via SSE (`GET /api/events`). Each event is a single `data:` line with JSON payload and `event:` type tag. The browser accumulates in a client-side circular buffer (default 10000).\n\n3. Embedded HTTP server (src/web_server.c): minimal HTTP/1.1 server. No external library dependency -- SSE is trivial to implement (write headers, then `fprintf(conn, \"event: %s\\ndata: %s\\n\\n\", type, json)`; no framing protocol). Serves compiled-in static assets (xxd -i at build time). Handles SSE via keep-alive connections. Non-blocking I/O integrated into the supervisor's event loop (epoll alongside seccomp notification FD). Bind to 127.0.0.1 by default.\n\n4. Frontend SPA (web/): vanilla JavaScript + Chart.js. No React, no build toolchain, no npm.\n   - index.html: layout with chart containers, event feed, system overview.\n   - js/state.js: shared state, EventSource connection, Chart.js config.\n   - js/charts.js: time-series instances (scheduler, memory, I/O, network). Stacked area for memory, bar for interrupts.\n   - js/events.js: scrolling event feed, color-coded by type, filterable, click-to-expand.\n   - js/gauges.js: SVG gauges (context switch rate, memory pressure, FD occupancy).\n   - js/polling.js: 3s polling of /api/snapshot for state updates. Reconnect logic for SSE via EventSource.\n   - js/controls.js: time range, event filters, chart zoom (Chart.js zoom plugin), pause/resume via POST /api/control.\n   - style.css: dark/light theme, responsive layout.",
            "old_string": "#### Architecture\n\nThe web observatory is an optional component activated by `--web[=PORT]` (default port 8080). When enabled, the supervisor spawns an embedded HTTP server that serves the dashboard SPA and streams kernel telemetry over WebSocket. When disabled (the default), kbox has zero web dependencies and no listening sockets.\n\nDesign decisions informed by studying two reference implementations:\n- kula (externals/kula): Go-based server monitor. Demonstrates the embedded HTTP server + WebSocket push + Chart.js frontend pattern. Single binary, zero external dependencies, tiered ring-buffer storage for historical data, vanilla JavaScript with no framework. Key lesson: a single-binary architecture with embedded static assets (via compile-time embedding) is the right deployment model for a tool that must remain dependency-free.\n- tinyclaw (externals/tinyclaw): Node.js/Next.js multi-agent dashboard. Demonstrates SSE for event streaming, REST for state queries, and a rich interactive UI (Kanban, office simulation, org chart). Key lesson: SSE is simpler than WebSocket for unidirectional event feeds, but WebSocket is better when the client needs to send control messages (pause, filter, time range selection). The decoupled frontend/backend model (API server + separate SPA) is clean but adds deployment complexity that kbox should avoid.\n\nkbox adopts kula's single-binary, embedded-asset, WebSocket-push architecture, adapted for kernel telemetry instead of host system metrics:\n\n```\nLKL kernel (in-process)          kbox supervisor\n+----------------------+    +---------------------------+\n| scheduler counters   |    | seccomp dispatch loop     |\n| page cache stats     |<---| telemetry sampler (100ms) |\n| interrupt counters   |    | event logger              |\n| VFS operation counts |    |                           |\n| memory allocator     |    | embedded HTTP server      |\n| network stack stats  |    |   +- GET / (SPA)          |\n+----------------------+    |   +- GET /api/snapshot    |\n                            |   +- WS  /ws              |\n                            +-----------+---------------+\n                                        | WebSocket push\n                                        v\n                              +--------------------+\n                              | Browser dashboard  |\n                              | (Chart.js, vanilla |\n                              |  JS, embedded CSS) |\n                              +--------------------+\n```\n\nComponents:\n\n1. Telemetry sampler (src/web_telemetry.c): runs on a timer (default 100ms, configurable via --web-interval). Each tick reads LKL kernel data structures directly from the supervisor's address space:\n   - Scheduler: nr_context_switches (from runqueue), nr_running, current task comm/pid, EEVDF vruntime and deadline of the current task, per-policy task counts (SCHED_OTHER, SCHED_FIFO, SCHED_RR, SCHED_BATCH, SCHED_IDLE).\n   - Interrupts: softirq counts (from kernel_stat per-CPU arrays -- TIMER, NET_RX, NET_TX, BLOCK, SCHED, etc.), hardirq counts (virtio block, virtio net completions).\n   - Memory: buddy allocator free pages per order (from zone->free_area[]), slab cache occupancy (active objects, total slabs per cache), page cache size (from global_node_page_state), anonymous page count, total/free/available memory.\n   - Page faults: pgfault/pgmajfault counters from vm_event_states. These are meaningful in LKL when the guest triggers file-backed mmap faults through shadow FDs.\n   - VFS: counts of open/read/write/close/stat/getdents operations (instrumented in seccomp_dispatch.c, not LKL-internal -- this counts supervisor-level dispatches, which correspond 1:1 to guest syscalls).\n   - Block I/O: sectors read/written, I/O requests completed (from the virtio-blk device stats or block layer accounting).\n   - Network (when --net enabled): packets TX/RX, bytes TX/RX, TCP connection count, from LKL's net_device stats and SNMP counters.\n   The sampler packages these into a compact JSON snapshot and pushes to all connected WebSocket clients.\n\n2. Event logger (src/web_events.c): captures discrete kernel events (not periodic samples) and streams them as they occur:\n   - Syscall dispatch events: syscall name, args summary, disposition (LKL forward / CONTINUE / EPERM / ENOSYS), return value, latency_ns. Generated from the dispatch loop (complements --trace-format=json from Group E but with structured WebSocket delivery instead of stdout).\n   - Context switch events: prev task -> next task, reason (voluntary yield, preemption, sleep). Requires a lightweight hook at schedule() or __schedule() -- either a kprobe-style trampoline or a compile-time instrumentation point in LKL.\n   - Page fault events: faulting address, fault type (minor/major), resolution (page cache hit, disk read, COW). Requires instrumentation at handle_mm_fault or the page fault entry.\n   - Process lifecycle: fork (clone3 dispatch), exec (forward_execve), exit (forward_exit_group). Already observable from the dispatch loop.\n   - Memory allocation events (optional, high volume): __alloc_pages order and gfp_mask, kmem_cache_alloc cache name. Sampled (not every allocation) to avoid overwhelming the WebSocket.\n   Events are timestamped (clock_gettime CLOCK_MONOTONIC) and delivered as individual JSON messages on the WebSocket. The browser accumulates them in a circular buffer (configurable, default 10000 events).\n\n3. Embedded HTTP server (src/web_server.c): minimal HTTP/1.1 server, no external library dependency. Serves the SPA from compiled-in static assets (HTML, JS, CSS converted to C byte arrays at build time via xxd or a custom script, similar to kula's go:embed pattern). Handles WebSocket upgrade (RFC 6455 -- the protocol is simple enough to implement in ~300 lines of C; alternatively, link against a minimal WebSocket library like libwebsockets or wslay if the complexity exceeds what's reasonable for